{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_anaconda_ver01/data/sn85053045/00517178172/1958010201/0002.xml":{"full_text":"THE GLACIER REPORTER\nOfficial Newspaper of Glacier County and Town of Browning\nPublished at Browning, Montana every Thursday\nEntered eerond diu melUnf matter at the Post Office\nBrowning, Montana, under the Act of March 3, 187 y.\nM. K. Fields. Publisher\nNAIIO NA I fD \u2022T 0- A t Subwr.Mlon Rate:\nI I ASSOCIATION 1 Year in Glacier County $3 00\nMonths in Glacier Co. SI \"5\nmilUimiiUU j Year out of Glacier Co. S 3 50\n6 Months out of County S2OO\nSin\u00dfle Copy 10\nL ALL subscriptions strictly in\nADVANCS NO SUBSCRIPTION\nVwJ 1 LISS THAN 4 MONTHS\nWeekly News Report On Doings\nUnder The Dome In Washington\nThe Recession of 1954\u2014\nThe Next Six Months\u2014\nThe Needed 13 Billions\u2014\nDefense To Cost More\u2014\nWASHINGTON. Jan 5 The\nrecession which is now underway\nand w hich has been felt by some\nsegments of the economy already\nwill continue its course until the\nsummer It may reach full swing\nbetween April and June, but in\ncreased government expenditures\nmight help take up the slack by\nthe time Congress adjourns\nwhich is estimated now as Au\ngust\nThe Internal Revenue Service\nwill feel the recession heavily in\nApril, and also in the current\nmonth, as tax payments are made\nThe unemployed do not pay tax\nes and the number of unemploy\ned may reach 5 million by March\nMoreover, business profitshave\nnot been what some expected and\nthis will cut down on government\nrevenue. As the recession contin\nues more and more business men\nwill cut inventories, as they al\nways do in a recessionary period\nThis tends to aggrevate the sit\nuation although it makes for a\nbrisk spur when things begin to\npick up again.\nOne of the keys to the unfold\ning picture is the farm program,\nand how the farmer fares in 1958\nA good year, perhaps a more ef\nfective farm program, might do\nmuch to pick up business in the\nfall, although the farmer's buy\ning power today is only a little\nover 10 per cent of the national\ntotal.\nThe downward turn of the stock\nmarket is looked upon by some\nas a healthy long-term develop\nment. Certainly the prices of com\nmon stocks are dropping to the\npoint where a big break\u2014a crash\n\u2014is highly unlikely. For those\nwho haven't seen prices of their\nstocks dip this should be encour\naging news.\nThe view of many economists is\nthat the recession was begging\nunnoticed\u2014when stocks began to\nskid in the last months of 1957\nChristmas business and the last\nquarter of the year always show'\ncomparative strength and 1957\nwas no exception. The test will\ncome in the first and second\nquarters of this year\nThe secret \u2022Gaither' report,\nwhich was reported on in this\ncolumn four weeks ago. recently\nwas the subject of a much-publi\ncized copyrighted article in \u2022The\nWashington Post\nWhat that article contained was\nreported in substance in this co!\numn a month ago\u2014even though\nthe wire services played the story\nas a first-run scoop The article\ndid mention figures when it dis\ncussed recommendations of the\ncommittee which looked into our\nchances in case of a war with\nRussia\nThe committee, as reported in\nthis column, recommended the\nUnited States step up its spend\ning on defense tremendously It\nalso recommended the govern\nment begin a huge construction\nprogram\u2014construction of fall-out\nshelters for the American people.\nThis program alone would cost\nup to five billions of dollars an\nnually. And the committee thinks\nthat more than this should be\nadded to our already-heavy de\nfense spending, which approach\ned 40 billion dollars in the cur\nrent fiscal year.\nCongress seems certain to in\ncrease defense spending consider\nably at the coming session, but\nwhether it will hike the figure to\nmore than 50 billion\u2014as has been\nrecommended is extremely\ndoubtful\nIt is known that the President\nis planning to ask Congress to\nstop certain programs and expen\nditures which are non-essential\nand some sokins may howl about\nthis when the time comes, but no\nfunds are to be included in the\nbudget for these positioned pro\ngrams.\nit takes months of technical\nschooling and training to teach\nyoung men and women to oper\nate. repair, and maintain the US\nArmy's modern weapons and ma\nchines. High school graduates\u2014\nAre you interested?\nIf you are a high school gradu\nate you will be able to find the\nriMt course from the more than\nIN ottered by the US Army.\nA MINUTE\nWITH Ml\n\n1 don\u2019t suppose it \u00abill make an\nawful lot of differen. e. m his\nsalary but Ea defim'ely\nshowing signs ot grow mg up Ac\ncording to the late*\u2019 report he\nhas given up h.s collection ot\nTeddy Bears and 'hipped them\nito a childrens home\nI This action, it could be assum\ned. was prompted by ins pending\ninduction into the armed forces\nThe n port also stated that he\nlitas been granted a 60 day re\npnevv in order to give iiim time\nto finish a picture\nAin t that tin life rva They\ndid: e\\<n give me time to w \u2014d\nup my l>usme\" a::....- Weil,\n'there ar< a lot of us who will\nbe hoping that his voice will\nchange as well a- hobbit\nnow that lie i' growing up'\nVery frequently w, get request\nfor reproduction- of the picture\nwe print in tin pa per so at this\ntime we would like to state that\nthey w.l! be av.ul.ible tiirough\nour local photographer. 1) n\nSchmidt of tb.e Glacier Studio\nWhile we do take our own\npictures and process them for\nuse in the paper we du nut re\nproduce them f r sale We do\nnot hate the time to do so. and\nthe studio can do a much better\njob than we can because that is\ntheir specialty So. in the\nifuture. for those who wish pic-\nI tures. please send y. ur requests\nto the Glacier Studio. Popular\nsizes are 5 x 7 or 8 x In\nJust m case you didn\u2019t get\nyour greeting from the Bureau\nof Interna! Revenue, dm\u2019, be\ndisappointed It will catch up\nwith you This is one department\nof the government that always\nseems to be able to locate y u\nregardless of whether or not you\nleave a forwarding address\nSort of funny how they oper\nate They tax you for everything\nOW^''Mac\nBABY SITTING\u2014is a tiresome job at a dance as the expression on this young lady's face will indi\ncate Youngsters only able to walk soon learn the steps and participate in the fun. However, along\ntowards midnight some of them tin- and curl up on the floor in blankets, then a baby sitter takes\nover while the others continue to dance.\nI V''\nINDIAN MAIDENS, young and old. participate in the dance festivities adding more color to the\noccasion The younger women dress in buckskin dresses, beautifully beaded, and wear head bands\nwhile the older ones usually wear brightly colored dresses. The women do not wear ankle bells as\ndo the men but gracefully dance to the rhythm and beat of the drum, enjoying the performance\nfully as well as the men. 1\nTHE GLACIER REPORTER, BROWNING. GLACIER COUNTY, MONTANA\nbut the air you breathe, then\nspend thousands of dollars to\npublish and mail literature tell\ning you how to save money by\ntaking the proper precautions.\n\nWe hope you will forgive us\nfor this abbreviated edition. We\nswore once never to drop down\nto four pages again, but things\nhave happened so fast since\nChristmas that we just had to\ncut down somewhere to please\neveryone.\nIt is at this time of the year\nthat everyone suddenly realizes\nthey are out of statements, en\nvelopes. stationery and all of\ntheir other printing needs, so\nthey come rushing in ail out of\nbreath and with tears in their\neyes, pleading for immediate\nservice We try to give it to\nthem, hut we have taken another\noath to the effect that we will\nn work over 25 hours a day as\nall work and no play is making\na dull boy out of Mi and the\nrest of the gang.\nSo for this time, we ask you\nto go along with us. We rather\nieel like the mother who was\nexpecting one. but when it was\nover she wound up with triplets.\nfrom the looks of things on\nW,dnesday there was another\nepidemic of Seven Crown Flu\naround town Symptoms seem to\nlie a red nose, red eyes, weak\nness in the knees, loss of appe\ntite and a craving for water. It\nusu: !ly takes only two or three\ndays to get over it. then the\nvictim is immuned for some time\nbut occasionally it is recur\nrent\nOne of the boys staggered into\ne shop Tuesday evening just\na- 1 was about to leave, carrying\na rather heavy load. \"What are\ny. u celebrating.'' I inquired, \"the\n.l.i year or the new one?\"\n1 don't know. he answered,\nbut if you will lend me two\nbucks that should take care of\nboth of them\n1 told him I didn't have two\nl ucks but reached into the gro\n.try bag and found a can of\nt >mato juice. Have a can of beer\non me. I said and handed it to\nhim Hi- took it and went away\nhappy What a life!\nEdward McManman\nRites Held Last Thursday\nFuneral services were held\nThursday. January 2. at East Gla\ncier for Edward McManman. who\npassed away last Sunday. Decem\nber 29 at the Latch-String Rest\nHouse at East Glacier where he\niiad been a resident .for over\nseven years\nMr McManman celebrated his\n92nd birthday November 9\nSurvivors include two sisters.\nMrs R P Baker of St Paul.\nMinnesota and Mrs Anna 1.\nMurphy of Bahglon. .New York:\ntwo nephews. John Baker of St.\nPaul, and Dan R Baker, who ar\nrived at Browning December 31\nto attend the funeral service.\nLbw Enforcement Officer\nLists Improvements\nNecessary For Safety\nConstable Ernest Gray early\nthis week expressed the hope\nthat immediate future attention\ncould soon be directed toward\nwhat he expressed as \"major im\nprovements\" needl'd in our com\nmunity.\nThe improvements he listed as\nrequiring prompt consideration\nwere the intallation of a stop\nlight which he said constitutes\nnecessity toward overall traffic\nsafety and elimination of acci\ndents: street numbers, and the\nsanding of streets at periodic in\ntervals during the winter months\nwhen icy and slippery conditions\nrepresent a threat to the safety\nof both passenge. cars and pe\ndestrians.\nGray said it is hoped that local\ncivic organization.- may in the\nfuture give some thought and\nconsideration to \"banding togeth\ner\" in an attempt to bring about\nan immediate correction to these\nexistei.t condition- at a near fu\nture date\nAre you interested m boats,\nmotor vehicles, or railroading?\nIf so and you are a high school\ngraduate or have the equivalent\nof a high school education, the\nUS Army will enlist you for a\ncourse in any of these fields\nSee Us For Job Printing\nDoings Of The\nAmerican Legion\nby Tom Jesseppe\nA full house of children under\n12 years old and all students\nat the Cut Bank boarding school\nduring the holiday- were treated\nto free movies at the local the\nater on Tuesday afternoon. De\ncember 24.\nA western movie, two shorts\nand cartoons were shown to an\nappreciative audience\nThreatening blizzards during\nthe holiday held attendance to\nabout half of last year's record\nattendance Only a few children\nfound it expedient to sit in the\naisles.\nThe showing wasp -sored by\nthe Blackfeet India- Re-erv ation\nPost 127 of the American Legion\nand James Leadbetter manager\nof the Park Theater\nArt Engdah! pla: t. resign his\nemployment wuJi .1 dm Harper\nand the Amen an Legion club\nand assume similar duties at\nBabb on January 1 The mem\nbeis have enjoyed many pleas\nant associations with Art. and.\nalong ith wishing him the best\nof everything, may a more profit\nable venture be a big item among\nhis blessings for the coming year\nHe has encouraged several mem\nbers to join our post. We ap\npredate his interest and loyalty\nto the organization.\n\nFrank MacCormick and Frank\nJuneau will attend the midwinter\nconference of the American Le\ngion of Montana in Helena in\nmid January. This is a confer\nence of Legion leaders through\nout the state to review the past\nyear's program and to plan for\nthe coming year. As chairman of\ntheir respective committees, Mac-\nCormick will give a report on\nBoy Scout activities, and Juneau\nwill give a report on the activi\nties of the Safety Committee.\nPerhaps they will bring back a\nreport on the present status of\nthe proposed Korean War bonus.\nThis is written on the last day\nof 1957. tlie year Browning re\nceived its first and so far only\nchannel on live television from\nstudios in Lethbridge. Alberta.\nWe were able to pick up the\nthird and succeeding games of\nthe world series between the\nNew York Yankees and the Mil\nwaukee Braves, with the Braves\nwinning the series. Boxing and\nwrestling on Friday nights are\npopular So far no football games\nbetween U.S. colleges have been\ntelevised into Browning The\nfirst will be televised tomorrow\nbetween Rose Bowl contestants\nOhio State and Oregon.\nOur neighboring town of Cut\nBank, through use of reflector\nr 3\nfood Buys\nGarden Grown 303 2 For\nASPARAGUS 55c\nKuners 303 2 For\nKIDNEY BEANS 55c\nSummer Garden 2 For\nSLICED BEETS 29c\nFlavorpack 303 2 For\nSLICED CARROTS 35c\nKuners No. 2 2 For\nHOMINY 29c\nColumbia 303 2 For\nKRAUT 25c\nLarsons 303 3 For\nVEGALL 39c\nDel Monte 393 2 For\nNEWSPUDS 29c\nHunts 300 2 For\nSPINACH 25c\nDel Monte 303 2 For\nPEAS CARROTS 43c\nDel Monte 303 2 For\nSTEWED TOMATOES 39c\nFlavorpack 303 2 Fer\nRHUBARB 45c\nVelveeta 2 Lb.\nCHEESE FOOD 83c\nFamily Size 20 Oi. 4 For\nCATSUP M.OO\nBronko 2 For\nGrapefruit Sections 37c\nComstock 2 Fer\nSLICED APPLES 43c\nCoeur d' Atone 2 For\nAPPLESAUCE 29c\nWu Give S 4 H Green Stamps. Seve Them For Velueble Premiums\nTEEPLE\u2019S MARKET\nWKK MH HOMtOWNID STOM Muvmv\ns a.m. to r p.m. Browning, Montana *daTlv*\nand cable systems, has access to\nthree channels, being able to\npick up images from Lethbridge.\nGreat Falls and Spokane. No\ndoubt Cut Bankers will have a\nchoice of viewing more than one\nbowl game on New Years day.\nSeveral local entertainers have\nappeared at the Lethbridge sta\ntion to be seen in Browning\nhomes. Among them have been\na group of dancers from the local\nschool; also the Starr School\nFancy (Indian) Dancers, under\nthe able tutelage of Earl Old\nPerson. Tribal Councilman, liar\nold Anderson played the piano\nand sang one evening 1957 marks\nthe advent of live television into\nthe Browning area.\nIn the field of radio a \"first\nwas scored during 1957 wh e n\nDelano\nGranite Works\nWorld's Largest Rotoilers Of\nMemorials\nDAVID KRAFT\nLocal Representative\n318 Bth Ave South\nShelby, Montana\nPackrite 303 5 Fer\nAPRICOTS 89c\nEarly Garden M 3 S For\nPEACHES *I.OO\nWestpac M 3 5 For\nPEARS *I.OO\nStevens S For\nPIE CHERRIES 98c\nHeart of Uteh 303 7 Fer\nTOMATOES 99c\nBUTTER 65c\n2 Dot.\nEGGS 85c\nFRESH PEANUTS 69c\nMEXICORN 89c\nLakeland n\nMARGARINE 98c\n12 For\nPINK GRAPEFRUIT 99c\nPICNIC HAMS 39c\nSLICED BACON 63c\n(Beat Grado)\nBEEF TONGUE 29c\nBEEF LIVER 29c\nThursday, January 2, 1958\nPeter Red Horn, the Blackfeet\nTribal Council\u2019s public relations\nhead obtained free of charge\nfrom the management of Station\nKIYI 15 minutes of radio time\nevery other Friday night to air\nBlackfeet affairs. The program\nwill be aired this Friday evening\nagain, and every other Friday\nthereafter.\nAny Day\nAny Time\nAny Place\nWe're Available\n\nJ. L. Sherburne Agency\nfaithe s. bercovich\n\nPhone FEB-2470\nFirst National Bank Building\nBrowning","height":"23972","width":"17744"}}
